qx|min,Responder's minimum rebids|
nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|5|fp|t|at|
^-{ Responder's minimum rebids }
^-|fp||at|
Your partner opens the bidding with 1 of a suit. You respond with a new suit bid, promising at least 6 total points and at least 4 cards in the suit named. Your partner rebids in another new suit and it is your turn to rebid. How do you make your decision?
|ht|h|cs|1|at|^-{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
^-
|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


at|The subject of responder's rebids is not a simple one. This is due to the fact that there are many ways the bidding can go before responder has a chance to take a second bid. Sometimes the opener will be limited, but sometimes he will not be. In the bidding above, for example, opener could have either a minimum (13-15) or a medium (16-18) hand.

One of the luxuries that responder has when choosing his rebid is that pass is usually an option. Almost all of opener's rebids (including his new suit rebid above) are non-forcing.

|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{Responder is usually allowed to pass at his turn to rebid, but he
should try to keep the bidding going if a game contract is still possible.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


at|In other words, the responder should only pass at his second turn if he knows that a game contract is impossible (and if he thinks the strain of opener's rebid should be reasonable).|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Just like the rebid of the opening bidder, the responder's rebid classifies his hand into 1 of 3 ranges, namely minimum, medium, or maximum. The total point ranges for these categories are different for the responder than the ranges we learned for the opener:

|cs|3|at|^-{Responder places his hand into one of these categories: minimum (6-9), medium (10-11),
or maximum (12 or more). Responder's rebid limits his hand to one of these 3 ranges.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


cs|1|at|There are some useful consequences of categorizing both the opener and the responder as either minimum, medium, or maximum:

^-{If opener has shown a minimum (13-15) hand, responder knows to signoff in a partial
if he is also minimum, invite game if he is medium, and force to game if he is maximum.}
^-
This should be easy to understand. Suppose opener's rebid promised a minimum hand (13-15 total points). If responder is also minimum, with 6-9 total points, he knows that the partnership cannot have the 25 combined total points for a game contract. He should try to sign off in the best strain at as low a level as possible.

If responder has a medium hand with 10 or 11 total points, he knows that game will be reasonable if opener is near the top of his 13-15 total point range. He can express this opinion by making an invitational rebid.

If responder has a maximum hand with 12 or more total points, he knows a game contract is certain as the partnership must have 25 or more combined total points. In this case, the responder must force to game with his rebid.|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Here is what responder knows about the partnership's game prospects when the opener promises either a medium or a maximum hand with his rebid:
|cs|4|n#|8|at|^-{If opener has shown a medium (16-18) hand, responder will either signoff in a partial
or invite game if he is minimum, but will force to game if he is medium or maximum.}

|cs|2|at|{If opener has shown a maximum (19-21) hand, his rebid created a game force. Opener
will have promised enough combined total points for game even if responder is minimum.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


at|If the responder has a complete minimum with 6 total points he will know that game is out of reach opposite a medium (16-18) opening. With 7 or 8 total points the responder should invite game opposite a medium opener. 9 total points are enough for responder to force to game if opener is medium. Rebidding opposite a maximum opener is quite easy. In many cases a maximum opener will rebid the best game contract and responder can pass. 

|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


at|Responder's most difficult rebidding decisions are when both his response and opener's rebid have been in new suits. Responder's task is difficult in this case because he does not yet know if the opener is minimum or medium.

|cs|1|at|^-{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
^-
Our first examples of responder's rebid will be continuations after this difficult sequence of bids.|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2
The responder has 4 ways of describing a minimum hand with his rebid:

|cs|1|ht|f|at|^B{|ia| 1cp1Hp1spp|at|} 
|cs|2|ht|d|at|^C {By passing a non-forcing bid.}
|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


cs|1|ht|f|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp1n|at|}
|cs|2|ht|d|at|^Q   {By rebidding 1NT.}
|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


ht|n|cs|1|at|^B{|ia| 1cp1Hp1sp2h|at|}
|cs|2|ht|l|at|^C   {By rebidding the same suit.}|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


cs|2|ht|l|at|^P{By raising one of partner's suits.}
|ht|n|cs|1|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1Hp1sp2s|at|}

|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


cs|1|at|The following minimum rebid, when responder goes back to opener's first suit, is usually referred to as a preference (and not as a raise). We will see why in a moment.

^-{|ia| 1cp1Hp1sp2c|at|}
|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Here are some examples of responder's rebids with minimum hands (6-9 total points):|
cs|1|ht|d|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|c|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|psj42hat763dt632ct|at|}

|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


at|^^Pass - do not rebid at all. This hand has only 6 total points (5 HCP and 1 long suit point). Game is out of reach even if partner is at the top of the medium range. Your hearts are not strong enough to rebid and you lack the diamond stopper that 1NT would suggest. Since you prefer spades to clubs you should pass 1@S and expect to be in a reasonable partial contract.|
cs|1|ht|d|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1spp|at|}|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


cs|1|ht|p|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|o|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|pcj42hat763dt632st|at|}

|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


at|^^Rebid 2@C, taking a preference back to opener's first bid suit. This hand is the same as the last one except that the spades and clubs have been switched. This time you prefer partner's first suit. Let him know that by taking preference to clubs. You are not showing any extra strength by taking a second bid. You are only saying that you like clubs better than spades and that your hand is unsuitable for any other minimum rebid.|
cs|1|ht|p|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp2c|at|}|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|
cs|1|ht|c|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|b|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|pcj4hkqjt8dt632st2|at|}

|
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


at|^^Rebid 2@H. This hand, with 8 total points, is stronger than the hands we just saw, but it is still well within the minimum (6-9) range. Responder should try to have at least 6 cards in his suit to bid it again, but a strong 5-card suit (such as this one) will do in a pinch. Responder really is in a pinch on this hand which lacks good support for both of partner's suits and does not have a diamond stopper for notrump. Fortunately, the strong 5-card heart suit comes to the rescue.|
cs|1|ht|c|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp2h|at|}|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


cs|1|ht|p|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|o|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|pc73hA97532dqjtst4|at|}

|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


at|^^Rebid 2@H again. This 6-card heart suit is not very strong, but any 6-card suit is strong enough for responder to bid twice. Do not rebid 1NT just because you have a diamond stopper. It is more important to show your extra length in hearts, a major suit.|
cs|1|ht|p|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp2h|at|}|
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


ht|y|cs|2|at|^-{Responder can bid any 6-card suit or a strong 5-card suit a second time at his rebid.}
|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|
cs|1|ht|c|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|b|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|pcst62hkj84dat96c85|at|}

|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


at|^^Rebid 1NT. This hand has 8 total points (all in HCP) which puts it in the minimum range. Having a stopper in the unbid suit (diamonds in this case) is one of the main requirements of responder's 1NT rebid. The other main requirement is the inability to raise partner or to bid the same suit a second time. This hand clearly meets all of the requirements for a 1NT rebid. The fact that this hand is balanced is a nice bonus.|

cs|1|ht|c|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp1n|at|}|

cs|1|ht|p|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|o|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|ps5chhk9764dqjt84ct2|at|}

|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


at|^^Rebid 1NT again. Ideally this rebid should be used to show a balanced hand, but it is the only good choice with this unbalanced hand. The 5-card heart suit is not strong enough to bid a second time. You have a 5-card diamond suit that you have not shown yet, but 2@D (the last new suit) would not show a minimum hand. The good news is that you have a stopper in diamonds, the unbid suit.|
cs|1|ht|p|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp1n|at|}
|
pg| ***** 31 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|
cs|1|ht|c|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|b|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|psq982hat84d6ct942|at|}

|
pg| ***** 32 ***** |


at|^^Raise to 2@S. At first it looks like you should pass this hand with 6 total points now that a trump fit has been found. Remember, since a raise is being considered, add 3 short suit points for the singleton diamond. Now this hand is worth 9 total points and 4@S should have a good chance if opener has a medium hand. Give him one last chance to tell you if he has any extra strength.
|n#|8|cs|2|at|^-{When responder raises opener's second suit he is promising at least 4-card support.}
^-
|cs|1|ht|c|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp2s|at|}|
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


cs|1|ht|p|n#|8|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|o|n#|8|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|ps7haK34d8742cj865|at|}
|
pg| ***** 34 ***** |


n#|8|at|^^Rebid 2@C, showing your preference for partner's first suit. This preference feels more like a raise as the hand contains 4-card support for clubs. Why don't the 3 short suit points for the singleton spade push this hand above the 6-9 total point range of minimum hands? The answer is that you should only count short suit points in unbid suits. Partner has bid spades so we shouldn't count anything for our singleton spade. This hand is still worth only 8 total points.|
cs|1|ht|p|n#|8|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp2c|at|}|
pg| ***** 35 ***** |


qx|exercise4,hide Responder's minimum rebids - Exercises|
md||mb|1c|mb|p|mb|1h|mb|p|mb|1s|mb|p|
nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|5|at|
^-{Responder's minimum rebids - Exercises}
^-
|ht|d|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|ps5hjt8762da542cj5|at|}|
ht|e|cs|1|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}|
hf|k|cq|3|lb|*BYou are the responder.
Which rebid would you make?^^2h|
ht|e|cs|1|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp2h|at|}

Rebid 2@H. Any 6-card suit can be rebid by the responder and 2@H is the correct rebid with this minimum hand. This hand has the diamond stopper that a 1NT rebid would promise, but 2@H is a more sensible choice. This hand is unbalanced and rates to take several more tricks in hearts than it would in notrump.|
pg| ***** 37 ***** |


ht|p|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|pst54hk9543d863ck2|at|}|
ht|q|cs|1|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}|
hf|z|lb|*BYou are the responder.
Which rebid would you make?^^p|
ht|q|cs|1|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1hp1spp|at|}

Pass. Your 5-card heart suit is far too weak to rebid and you lack the diamond stopper that 1NT would promise. You aren't crazy about either of partner's suits, but you do have more spades than clubs. With such a minimum hand it is best to keep the contract low and pass partner in 1@S.|
pg| ***** 39 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|
ht|b|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|psk92hq9864dkt92c3|at|}|
ht|c|cs|1|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}|
hf|i|cq|3|lb|*BYou are the responder.
Which rebid would you make?^^1n|
ht|c|cs|1|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp1n|at|}


Rebid 1NT. This hand is close to the top of the minimum range. Opener could still have a medium (16-18 total point) hand so it is a good idea to take another bid. The hearts are too weak for 2@H and a 2@S raise would promise 4-card support. With a strong holding in diamonds, the unbid suit, 1NT is the correct rebid, even though this hand is unbalanced.|
pg| ***** 41 ***** |


ht|o|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|ps92hk9543d863ckt4|at|}|
ht|p|cs|1|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}|
hf|x|lb|*BYou are the responder.
Which rebid would you make?^^2c|
ht|p|cs|1|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp2c|at|}


Rebid 2@C, taking a preference back to opener's first suit. This is a very minimum response with no attractive rebid, but it would be wrong to pass now. You have a clear preference for clubs over spades. The heart suit is too weak for a 2@H rebid and the diamond suit is too weak for a 1NT rebid. Try 2@C and hope for the best.|
pg| ***** 43 ***** |


qx|med,Responder's medium rebids|
nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|5|fp|t|at|
^-{ Responder's medium rebids }
^-|fp||at|
A medium (10 or 11 total point) responder has 4 ways to invite a game contract:
|cs|1|ht|h|at|^B{|ia| 1cp1Hp1sp3c|at|} 
|cs|2|ht|f|at|^B    {By jump raising partner's first suit.}
|
pg| ***** 44 ***** |


cs|2|ht|f|at|^O {By jump raising partner's second suit.}
|ht|h|cs|1|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1Hp1sp3s|at|}
|
pg| ***** 45 ***** |


ht|p|cs|1|at|^B{|ia| 1cp1Hp1sp3h|at|}
|cs|2|ht|n|at|^B     {By jump rebidding the same suit.}
|
pg| ***** 46 ***** |


cs|1|ht|p|at|^O{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp2n|at|}
|cs|2|ht|n|at|^Q   {By rebidding 2NT.}

|
pg| ***** 47 ***** |


ht|u|at|All 4 of responder's above rebids are non-forcing, but highly invitational. The opener can pass when responder makes one of these rebids, but he is encouraged to go on to a game contract with any semblance of extra strength.

|
pg| ***** 48 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{Responder's medium rebids show 10 or 11 total points. Opener will insist on game with 
15 or more total points, pass with 13 total points, and use his judgement with 14 total points.}
|
pg| ***** 49 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|n#|5|at|Here are some examples of responder's rebids with medium hands (10-11 total points):|
cs|1|ht|d|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|c|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|ps6hak87d7642ckt53|at|}

|
pg| ***** 50 ***** |


at|^^Jump raise partner's first suit to 3@C (a jump preference). This hand has 10 total points, all in HCP. Remember that you should not count any short suit points for your singleton as partner has bid spades. You should try to have 4-card support for the jump preference of a minor suit, but 3-card support is acceptable if there are no good alternative rebids. 3-card support is sufficient for a jump preference in a major suit.|
cs|1|ht|d|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp3c|at|}|

cs|1|ht|p|n#|7|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|o|n#|7|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|psj983hak87d5c9872|at|}

|
pg| ***** 51 ***** |


at|^^Jump raise partner's second suit to 3@S. This time the singleton is in an unbid suit so this hand counts 3 short suit points. 11 total points (8 HCP and 3 short suit points) is too much for the minimum rebid of 2@S. An invitational rebid is called for and our 4-card support for spades points to 3@S as the best choice. This hand also contains 4-card support for clubs, but raising a major suit takes priority over raising a minor suit.|
cs|1|ht|p|n#|7|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp3s|at|}|
pg| ***** 52 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|1|ht|c|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|b|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|pcs84haqt982dk96c42|at|}

|
pg| ***** 53 ***** |


at|^^Rebid 3@H. The jump rebid of responder's suit suggests a medium hand with a strong 6-card (or longer) suit. This hand contains 11 total points (9 HCP and 2 long suit points). It is clearly a medium hand and the 6-card heart suit is strong enough for a jump rebid. 3@H is just right, both in terms of strength and in terms of hearts.|
cs|1|ht|c|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp3h|at|}|

cs|1|ht|o|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|n|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|ps84hj76543dakqc42|at|}

|
pg| ***** 54 ***** |


at|^^Rebid 2NT, not 3@H. This 6-card heart suit is too weak for a jump rebid. Like most notrump bids that we have seen, only HCP are used to define responder's 2NT rebid. This rebid suggest 10-11 HCP and at least one stopper in the unbid suit (diamonds in this case).|
cs|1|ht|o|at|^N{|ia| 1cp1hp1sp2n|at|}|
pg| ***** 55 ***** |


ht|x|cs|2|at|^-{It would be nice if responder's 2NT rebid promised a balanced hand, but 2NT is often the
least of evils rebid with some unbalanced medium hands (such as the above example).}
|
pg| ***** 56 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|1|ht|c|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|b|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|pcsq6hkj74daj93ct43|at|}

|
pg| ***** 57 ***** |


at|^^Rebid 2NT. This balanced hand is a more classic example for responder's 2NT rebid. 2NT here shows 10-11 HCP with at least 1 stopper in the unbid suit. This 11 HCP hand with strong diamonds fits perfectly. The balanced nature of this hand makes a 2NT rebid look even better.|
cs|1|ht|c|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp2n|at|}|

cs|1|ht|n|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|m|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|ps8hkt764dakt65c52|at|}

|
pg| ***** 58 ***** |


at|^^Rebid 2NT again. Unfortunately there is no other choice with this unbalanced medium hand. Raising either of partner's suits is out of the question and the hearts are neither long enough nor strong enough for a jump rebid. It would be nice to get our second suit into the picture with a 2@D rebid, but a new suit rebid is not one of responder's choices when he is dealt a medium hand.|
cs|1|ht|n|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp2n|at|}|
pg| ***** 59 ***** |


ht|x|cs|2|at|^-{Ideally responder's 2NT rebid shows 10-11 HCP in a balanced hand with stoppers, but it
is frequently the case that 2NT is the least of evils rebid when responder is unbalanced.}
|
pg| ***** 60 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|cs|1|ht|c|at|^N {|ia| 1cp1hp1sp?|at|}
|ht|b|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|psa4hj9873d865ckqt|at|}

|
